\subsection{Motivation: Illustration of OR blow-up and SHAP mis-attribution}
With $p=0.80,\ q=0.85,\ \delta=0.10,\ \varepsilon=0.01$, all error rates remain in $(0.70,0.95)$, yet the OR diverges (Lemma~\ref{lem:minimal} and Corollary~\ref{corshap}):
\cgather{
\frac{\mathrm{OR}_{\text{naive}}}{\mathrm{OR}_{\text{true}}}
=\frac{(0.90)(0.25)}{(0.70)(0.05)}
=\frac{0.225}{0.035}\approx 6.43,
}
so $\mathrm{OR}_{\text{naive}}\approx 6.5$.  
This demonstrates strong inflation from small differential errors
under otherwise good $(p,q)$.

For a SHAP example, with $|\beta_k| = 1$, $\sigma_k = 1$, $\varepsilon = 0.05$, and $\sigma_j = 30$, we obtain $S_j/S_k \approx 1.5$ (Corollaries~\ref{corshap},\ref{corshap2}), meaning a feature with a coefficient $20\times$ smaller appears $50\%$ more important in SHAP attribution. Intuitively, SHAP scales importance by variance, so high-variance noise can dominate  for weak effects.

To illustrate $\SPOR$ applicability, Figure~\ref{figvolcano} compares three attribution strategies:  odds ratios (left), mean SHAP values (middle), and $\SPOR$ (right), applied to comorbidity data for IPF, ASD and ADRD, based on \zcor models. Each point corresponds to an ICD-coded condition, plotted by effect size on the x-axis and significance on the y-axis. While, applied to ADRD, IPF, and ASD cohorts, classical OR and SHAP attribute significance to an inflated fraction of diagnostic codes, with a striking number apparently “protective” (Fig.~\ref{figvolcano}, columns 1,2), $\SPOR$ suppresses these artifacts while preserving  plausible modulators, yielding a far more interpretable attribution landscape (Fig.~\ref{figvolcano}, column 3). 

