\section{Simulation Study}

\textbf{Design and data generation.}
We study estimation of a fixed $\theta=\log(\mathrm{OR})$ for a binary exposure $X\in\{0,1\}$ and outcome $Y\in\{0,1\}$ under outcome misclassification induced by a two-threshold selection on a calibrated predictive score for $Y$. We fix $\Pr(Y{=}1)=\pi$, a target $\log(\mathrm{OR})$, and the exposure prevalence $\Pr(X{=}1)=\varphi$. To generate $(X,Y)$, draw $Y\sim\mathrm{Bernoulli}(\pi)$ and $X\mid Y{=}y\sim\mathrm{Bernoulli}(\theta_y)$ with $(\theta_0,\theta_1)$ chosen to satisfy $\mathrm{OR}=\{\theta_1/(1-\theta_1)\}/\{\theta_0/(1-\theta_0)\}$ and $\varphi=\pi\theta_1+(1-\pi)\theta_0$, yielding a latent $2\times2$ table $T=\begin{bmatrix}a&b\\ c&d\end{bmatrix}$.

\textbf{Label noise via two ROC gates.}
Independently of the data generation above, we construct two operating points on the ROC of the score $S=f(\cdot)$: a high-specificity threshold $t_{\mathrm{hi}}$ and a lower score cut $t_{\mathrm{lo}}$ chosen to yield high selection-conditional specificity $q_{\mathrm{sel}}$. We include only the tails $H=\{S>t_{\mathrm{hi}}\}$ and $L=\{S<t_{\mathrm{lo}}\}$ (indicator $I=1\{H\cup L\}$), which induce selection-conditional sensitivity and specificity
$p_{\mathrm{sel}}=\Pr(\tilde Y=1\mid Y=1,I=1)$ and $q_{\mathrm{sel}}=\Pr(\tilde Y=0\mid Y=0,I=1)$.
This defines the misclassification operator
$K=\begin{bmatrix} p_{\mathrm{sel}} & 1-p_{\mathrm{sel}}\\[2pt] 1-q_{\mathrm{sel}} & q_{\mathrm{sel}}\end{bmatrix}$ and, in expectation, $\tilde T = T K^{\!\top}$.
Misclassification is non-differential with respect to $X$ because $I$ depends only on $S$.

\textbf{Correction by stabilized inversion.}
Given $(\tilde a,\tilde b,\tilde c,\tilde d)$ and $K$, we recover a feasible table by ridge-regularized inversion
\[
T^{(\lambda)} \;=\; \tilde T\,(K^{\!\top}+\lambda I)^{-1},
\]
choosing the \emph{smallest} $\lambda>0$ such that all entries of $T^{(\lambda)}$ are nonnegative and exceed a small floor $\varepsilon$ (feasibility rule). Writing $T^{(\lambda)}=\begin{bmatrix}\hat a&\hat b\\ \hat c&\hat d\end{bmatrix}$, the corrected estimator is
\[
\log(\lambda\text{-OR})=\log\hat a-\log\hat b-\log\hat c+\log\hat d.
\]
Uncertainty uses the classical multinomial variance $1/\hat a+1/\hat b+1/\hat c+1/\hat d$ plus the delta-method contribution from estimating $(p_{\mathrm{sel}},q_{\mathrm{sel}})$ on a validation cohort, yielding $\mathrm{SE}^2=\mathrm{Var}_{\text{base}}+\mathrm{Var}_{\text{extra}}$ and Wald intervals for $\log(\lambda\text{-OR})$.

\textbf{Metrics and grids.}
All performance is reported on the log scale against $\theta=\log(\mathrm{OR})$. For replicates $r=1,\ldots,R$, let $\widehat\ell_{r}^{\text{(naive)}}$ be the naive log-OR from $\tilde T$ and $\widehat\ell_{r}^{(\lambda\text{-OR})}$ the corrected log-OR from $T^{(\lambda)}$. We report
\[
\mathrm{Bias}=\tfrac1R\sum_{r}(\widehat\ell_r-\theta),
\mathrm{RMSE}=\sqrt{\tfrac1R\sum_{r}(\widehat\ell_r-\theta)^2},
\mathrm{Coverage}=\tfrac1R\sum_{r}\mathbf{1}\{\theta\in[\widehat\ell_r\pm1.96\,\widehat\sigma_r]\}.
\]
The primary grid increases misclassification by lowering $p_{\mathrm{sel}}$ while keeping $q_{\mathrm{sel}}$ high, with $m=1-p_{\mathrm{sel}}\in [0.05,0.20]$. The thresholds are chosen away from the ROC diagonal and the corners to balance purity and effective sample size. The same $R$ is used in every cell, so coverage changes in steps of $1/R$.

\textbf{Findings.}
As misclassification increases (See Fig.~\ref{fig:spor_three_panel}a-c), the naive $\log(\mathrm{OR})$ attenuates (bias drifts negative), RMSE inflates, and nominal 95\% coverage collapses. In contrast, $\log(\lambda\text{-OR})$ remains essentially unbiased over the same range, with modest RMSE growth and substantially higher coverage. The eventual coverage decline at the largest $m$ reflects intrinsic information loss as gates move toward the ROC diagonal together with the feasibility-enforcing ridge, rather than systematic miscalibration.



